'''Viðar Örn Kjartansson''' ({{IPA-is|ˈvɪːðar œrtn̥ ˈcʰar̥tansɔn}}; born 11 March 1990) is an Icelandic professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]] in Russia for [[FC Rubin Kazan|Rubin Kazan]], on loan from [[FC Rostov]].

==Club career==
Viðar made his debut for [[UMF Selfoss|Selfoss]] in 2006, aged 16. He joined Icelandic top division club [[Íþróttabandalag Vestmannaeyja|ÍBV]] in 2009 but rejoined Selfoss after a short stint with ÍBV.

He joined Icelandic club [[Fylkir]] in 2013 and after a very prolific goalscoring season in the Icelandic top flight, he joined Norwegian club [[Vålerenga Fotball|Vålerenga]] in December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vif-fotball.no/news/article/1jgepy3kfhbql16jgvuvcdp2gw/title/valerenga-signerer-vidar-orn-kjartansson |language=Norwegian |title=Vålerenga signerer Vidar Ørn Kjartansson |work=Vålerenga Fotbal |date=20 December 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303002627/http://www.vif-fotball.no/news/article/1jgepy3kfhbql16jgvuvcdp2gw/title/valerenga-signerer-vidar-orn-kjartansson |archive-date=3 March 2014 |dead-url=yes  }}</ref> 
Viðar scored his first goal for Vålerenga in a 3-1 home win over [[FK Bodø/Glimt|Bodø/Glimt]] on 6. April 2014.

After his first year in Norway, Viðar ended up as the top scorer in the Norwegian top league with 25 goals scored in 29 games.

On 22 January 2015, Viðar transferred to [[Chinese Super League]] side [[Jiangsu Guoxin-Sainty F.C.|Jiangsu Guoxin-Sainty]].<ref>[http://sports.sohu.com/20150122/n407996374.shtml 江苏舜天官方宣布签挪超金靴] at sports.sohu.com 22 January 2015 Retrieved 22 January 2015</ref> Jiangsu Guoxin-Sainty signed him for €3.5 million. On 7 March 2015, he made his debut and scored his first goal for Jiangsu in the first league match of the 2015 season which Jiangsu Sainty lost to [[Shanghai SIPG F.C.|Shanghai SIPG]] 2–1.<ref>[http://sports.sina.com.cn/j/2015-03-07/17307535288.shtml 中超-孔卡爆发策动两球 于海首球上港2-1舜天] at sports.sina.com 7 March 2015 Retrieved 11 March 2015</ref>

Viðar played a vital part in the Chinese FA cup, and was the club's top goalscorer in the cup with 4 goals, which helped Jiangsu to win their first trophy in history of the club.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}

On 27 January 2016, he signed for Swedish club [[Malmö FF]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/sportbladet/fotboll/sverige/allsvenskan/malmoff/article22160093.ab|title=Islänning klar för MFF|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mff.se/sv-SE/aktuellt/nyheter/Nyheter/2016-01-27_valkommen_till_mff_vidar_orn_kjartansson|title=Välkommen till Malmö FF, Vidar Örn Kjartansson - Malmö FF|website=www.mff.se}}</ref>

On 30 August 2016, he transferred to Israeli club [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]]. He signed a four-year deal with the club. On 26 October 2016 Viðar won the Swedish championship as Malmö FF sealed the title in his absence.

On 31 August 2018, he signed a four-year contract with the [[Russian Premier League]] club [[FC Rostov]], joining his compatriots [[Ragnar Sigurðsson]], [[Björn Bergmann Sigurðarson]] and [[Sverrir Ingi Ingason]] at the club.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[FC Rostov]]|url=http://www.fc-rostov.ru/press/news/11905|title=Видар Кьяртанссон — игрок "Ростова"!|trans-title=Vidar Kjartansson is a Rostov player!|date=31 August 2018|language=Russian}}</ref> He scored his first two goals for the club on 26 September 2018 in a [[Russian Cup (football)|Russian Cup]] 4–0 victory over a third-tier club [[FC Syzran-2003]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Russian Premier League]]|url=https://premierliga.ru/match/match_13066.html|title=Syzran-2003 - Rostov game report|language=Russian|date=26 September 2018}}</ref>

On 18 March 2019, Viðar signed a five-month loan deal with [[Hammarby Fotboll|Hammarby IF]] in Allsvenskan.<ref name="hammarby">{{cite web|publisher=[[Hammarby Fotboll]]|url=https://www.hammarbyfotboll.se/aktuellt/nyheter/hammarby-starker-anfallet-vidar-orn-kjartansson-lanas-in/|title=Hammarby stärker anfallet – Vidar Örn Kjartansson lånas in|language=Sweden|date=18 March 2019}}</ref>

On 20 July 2019, he joined Russian club [[FC Rubin Kazan]] on loan for the 2019–20 season.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[FC Rubin Kazan]]|url=https://www.rubin-kazan.ru/posts/vidar-kyartansson-v-rubine|title=ВИДАР КЬЯРТАНССОН – В «РУБИНЕ»|trans-title=Viðar Kjartansson in Rubin|date=20 July 2019|language=Russian}}</ref>

==International career==

Viðar made his senior international debut for [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] in 2014, starting as a centre forward in a friendly against [[Austria national football team|Austria]].<ref>http://www.espn.com/soccer/match?gameId=392328</ref> He scored his first international goal in a friendly against the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]] in January 2016.<ref>https://www.thenational.ae/sport/uae/uae-warm-up-for-world-cup-qualifiers-with-friendly-win-over-iceland-1.173578?videoId=5766484581001</ref> Despite a strong run for his club team [[Malmö FF]], Viðar was overlooked for a spot in Iceland's [[Euro 2016]] squad and instead put on the team's standby list.<ref>https://www.goal.com/en/news/veteran-gudjohnsen-earns-iceland-place-for-euro-2016/8mf0k97ym9ei1et4gb6diavjz</ref> His second international goal came in a friendly against [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]] in November 2017.<ref>https://www.skysports.com/football/qatar-vs-iceland/385549</ref> Viðar once again missed out on playing in an international championship, when he was left out of Iceland's [[World Cup 2018]] squad, serving as a non-squad reserve.<ref>https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/world-cup-squad-injured-gylfi-sigurdsson/17guw991qjit61qqhhfn9lyhon</ref>

Viðar announced his retirement from international duty in October 2018 at the age of 28, having won 19 caps and scored 2 goals.<ref>https://www.frettabladid.is/sport/vi%C3%B0ar-%C3%B6rn-h%C3%A6ttur-me%C3%B0-landsli%C3%B0inu</ref>

In March 2019, Viðar reversed his decision to retire from the national team and was called up to represent Iceland in the [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]] games against [[Andorra national football team|Andorra]] and [[France national football team|France]].<ref>https://www.frettabladid.is/sport/viar-oern-kallaur-inn-i-landslii</ref>

